You said:
i want .desktopHidden div text to be hidden in dekstop, and when it meets 768px, i want it to be visible.
ChatGPT said:

You can achieve this using CSS media queries. Heres the CSS to hide .desktopHidden text on desktop and show it when the screen width is 768px or smaller:

css
.desktopHidden {
    display: none; /* Hide by default on desktop */
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
    .desktopHidden {
        display: block; /* Show when screen width is 768px or smaller */
    }
}

This will ensure that the .desktopHidden div remains hidden on larger screens and becomes visible on tablets and smaller devices. Let me know if you need any modifications!

You said:
how to gain 50% width in a div size
ChatGPT said:

You can set a div's width to 50% using CSS or Tailwind CSS:

Using CSS

css
.myDiv {
    width: 50%;
}

html
<div class="myDiv">This div takes 50% width</div>

Using Tailwind CSS

html
<div class="w-1/2 bg-blue-500 p-4">This div takes 50% width</div>
  • w-1/2 Sets width to 50%.
  • bg-blue-500 Background color (optional).
  • p-4 Padding for better spacing (optional).

You said:
<h1> <KeyboardArrowRightIcon className={styles.trustedIcon} /> >200M </h1> it gives error for the > icon, how to overcome this error?
ChatGPT said:

The > symbol inside your JSX is being misinterpreted as a misplaced closing tag. To fix this, you have a few options:

Solution 1: Use HTML Entity (&gt;)

Replace > with &gt;

jsx
<h1>
  <KeyboardArrowRightIcon className={styles.trustedIcon} />&gt;200M
</h1>

Solution 2: Wrap in a <span>

This ensures proper rendering and avoids syntax issues:

jsx
<h1>
  <KeyboardArrowRightIcon className={styles.trustedIcon} />
  <span> >200M</span>
</h1>

Solution 3: Use Template Strings

If using inside {}, you can escape the symbol:

jsx
<h1>
  <KeyboardArrowRightIcon className={styles.trustedIcon} /> {" >200M"}
</h1>

Any of these solutions will fix the issue. Let me know if you need more help!

If you want the clip-path to create a diagonal cut from the top-left to the bottom-right corner, adjust your polygon like this:

css
clip-path: polygon(0 0, 100% 0, 100% 100%, 0 100%);

However, this doesn't create a diagonal cut. Instead, try this for a proper diagonal shape:

css
clip-path: polygon(0 0, 100% 0, 100% 100%, 0 100%);

If you meant a trapezoidal shape with a diagonal cut, use:

css
clip-path: polygon(0 0, 100% 0, 100% 100%, 20% 100%);

Visual Breakdown:

  • (0 0) Top-left corner
  • (100% 0) Top-right corner
  • (100% 100%) Bottom-right corner (adjust this for more slant)
  • (20% 100%) Bottom-left corner (adjust for the diagonal effect)

    display: flex;

    justify-content: center;
    color: white;
    padding: 50px;
}

Explanation of clip-path points:

  • (0 0) Top-left corner
  • (100% 0) Top-right corner
  • (100% 75%) Moves bottom-right up to create a diagonal effect
  • (0 100%) Bottom-left remains normal

HTML Example:

html
<section class="hero-section">
    <div>
        <h1>Legacy no longer</h1>

    </div>
</section>

        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold">Legacy no longer</h1>

You said:
does it will conflict import styles from "../Legacy/legacy.module.css"; import styles1 from "../HeroSection/heroSection.module.css";
ChatGPT said:

Yes, there could be a conflict when importing multiple CSS module files with the same variable name (styles).

Why Does It Conflict?

In your code:

js
import styles from "../Legacy/legacy.module.css";
import styles1 from "../HeroSection/heroSection.module.css";
  • The first import (styles) loads legacy.module.css.
  • The second import (styles1) loads heroSection.module.css without conflict because it has a unique name.

However, if you mistakenly import both as styles:

js
import styles from "../Legacy/legacy.module.css";
import styles from "../HeroSection/heroSection.module.css"; //  Conflict here!

This would cause an import error since styles is redefined.

How to Avoid Conflicts

  1. Use Different Variable Names

    js
    import legacyStyles from "../Legacy/legacy.module.css";
import heroStyles from "../HeroSection/heroSection.module.css";

    Then, use them accordingly:

    jsx
    <div className={legacyStyles.container}>Legacy Section</div>
<div className={heroStyles.container}>Hero Section</div>

  2. Merge Styles Using classnames (Optional) If you want to combine styles dynamically:

    sh
    npm install classnames

    js
    import classNames from "classnames";
import legacyStyles from "../Legacy/legacy.module.css";
import heroStyles from "../HeroSection/heroSection.module.css";

<div className={classNames(legacyStyles.container, heroStyles.hero)}>Content</div>

Conclusion

Your code (styles and styles1) wont conflict since they are different variables.
Avoid importing two CSS modules into the same styles variable to prevent errors.

Let me know if you need further clarification!
